codewords.meta_description: Test your code-breaking skills with Telegraph Codewords. Match numbers to letters, then fill in the grid. Play online today.

description.title: About Codewords
description.content: An engaging challenge for all ages and ability levels, The Telegraph’s complete collection of Codewords offers a range of daily challenges.

howto.title: How to play Codewords
howto.content: In Codewords, numbers are substituted for letters; work out which number corresponds to which letter, and use these to fill the grid. Some letters are already given; every letter is used at least once in the puzzle, and the completed grid contains no proper nouns. If you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

howto.title: How to play Kakuro
howto.content: Fill the grid using only the digits 1 to 9. The numbers in each block of white cells must add up to the total that appears above it or to its left, and you must not use the same number more than once in a block. The same digit can appear more than once in the same row or column, but must be in a separate block. You can use the Notes function to pencil in numbers that you aren't yet sure about; if you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

howto.title: How to play PlusWord
howto.content: Solve the crossword, then use the letters in the shaded squares to complete the additional PlusWord. A letter in a green square appears in the same column in the PlusWord as it does in the crossword; a letter in a yellow square appears in the PlusWord, but in a different column than it does in the PlusWord. There is only one possible answer for the PlusWord; it may be that the PlusWord contains letters that aren't in the crossword, but it can always be worked out logically without guessing. You can enter the PlusWord at any point, but you must complete both the crossword and the PlusWord to complete the puzzle.

howto.title: How to play Kakuro
howto.content: Fill the grid using only the digits 1 to 9. The numbers in each block of white cells must add up to the total that appears above it or to its left, and you must not use the same number more than once in a block. The same digit can appear more than once in the same row or column, but must be in a separate block. You can use the Notes function to pencil in numbers that you aren't yet sure about; if you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

howto.title: How to play PlusWord
howto.content: Solve the crossword, then use the letters in the shaded squares to complete the additional PlusWord. A letter in a green square appears in the same column in the PlusWord as it does in the crossword; a letter in a yellow square appears in the PlusWord, but in a different column than it does in the PlusWord. There is only one possible answer for the PlusWord; it may be that the PlusWord contains letters that aren't in the crossword, but it can always be worked out logically without guessing. You can enter the PlusWord at any point, but you must complete both the crossword and the PlusWord to complete the puzzle.

howto.content: In Codewords, numbers are substituted for letters; work out which number corresponds to which letter, and use these to fill the grid. description.content: Think differently with Telegraph Kakuro. Fill the grid with numbers for a fun and brain-boosting puzzle experience.

howto.title: How to play Kakuro
howto.content: Fill the grid using only the digits 1 to 9. The numbers in each block of white cells must add up to the total that appears above it or to its left, and you must not use the same number more than once in a block. The same digit can appear more than once in the same row or column, but must be in a separate block. You can use the Notes function to pencil in numbers that you aren't yet sure about; if you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

panagram.meta_description: Test your word-finding talents every day with Panagram. Create words with four or more letters, each including the middle letter. Play online now.

description.title: About Panagram
description.content: Rise through the ranks in our word-finding game. Create as many words as you can with four or more letters, including the nine-letter Panagram.

howto.title: How to play Panagram
howto.content: Create words of four letters or more, always using the centre letter. Proper nouns and plurals are not allowed, and you can only use each letter once per word. Can you find the nine-letter Panagram?

plusword.name: PlusWord
plusword.meta_title: PlusWord - Play Daily Online Games - Telegraph Puzzles
plusword.meta_description: A fun puzzle for all ages. Crack ten clues, fill in the grid, then use the shaded squares to find the PlusWord. Try it for yourself now.

description.title: About PlusWord
description.content: A fun puzzle for all ages. Crack ten clues as you fill in the grid, then use the different coloured squares to find the PlusWord.

howto.title: How to play PlusWord
howto.content: Solve the crossword, then use the letters in the shaded squares to complete the additional PlusWord. A letter in a green square appears in the same column in the PlusWord as it does in the crossword; a letter in a yellow square appears in the PlusWord, but in a different column than it does in the PlusWord. There is only one possible answer for the PlusWord; it may be that the PlusWord contains letters that aren't in the crossword, but it can always be worked out logically without guessing. You can enter the PlusWord at any point, but you must complete both the crossword and the PlusWord to complete the puzzle.

howto.title: How to play Sorted
howto.content: Each round presents a question on a related topic. You'll need to work out the correct order of the answers supplied (e.g most recent to oldest, or tallest to shortest). description.content: Think differently with Telegraph Kakuro. Fill the grid with numbers for a fun and brain-boosting puzzle experience.

howto.title: How to play Kakuro
howto.content: Fill the grid using only the digits 1 to 9. The numbers in each block of white cells must add up to the total that appears above it or to its left, and you must not use the same number more than once in a block. The same digit can appear more than once in the same row or column, but must be in a separate block. You can use the Notes function to pencil in numbers that you aren't yet sure about; if you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

howto.title: How to play Panagram

description.title: About PlusWord
description.content: A fun puzzle for all ages. Crack ten clues as you fill in the grid, then use the different coloured squares to find the PlusWord.

howto.title: How to play PlusWord
howto.content: Solve the crossword, then use the letters in the shaded squares to complete the additional PlusWord. A letter in a green square appears in the same column in the PlusWord as it does in the crossword; a letter in a yellow square appears in the PlusWord, but in a different column than it does in the PlusWord. There is only one possible answer for the PlusWord; it may be that the PlusWord contains letters that aren't in the crossword, but it can always be worked out logically without guessing. You can enter the PlusWord at any point, but you must complete both the crossword and the PlusWord to complete the puzzle.

howto.title: How to play Kakuro
howto.content: Fill the grid using only the digits 1 to 9. The numbers in each block of white cells must add up to the total that appears above it or to its left, and you must not use the same number more than once in a block. The same digit can appear more than once in the same row or column, but must be in a separate block. You can use the Notes function to pencil in numbers that you aren't yet sure about; if you get stuck, you can reveal individual cells or the entire solution at any point.

howto.title: How to play PlusWord
howto.content: Solve the crossword, then use the letters in the shaded squares to complete the additional PlusWord. A letter in a green square appears in the same column in the PlusWord as it does in the crossword; a letter in a yellow square appears in the PlusWord, but in a different column than it does in the PlusWord. There is only one possible answer for the PlusWord; it may be that the PlusWord contains letters that aren't in the crossword, but it can always be worked out logically without guessing. You can enter the PlusWord at any point, but you must complete both the crossword and the PlusWord to complete the puzzle.
